kura — an offline archive of YouTube.

kura captures a corner of YouTube — a video, a channel, a playlist, a search, or
a music album — into a self-contained, offline-browsable repository: every video
as a record, its transcript, comments and chapters, its images localised, and,
when you ask for it, the video and audio streams themselves, rendered into a
static site that plays offline and into clean Markdown you can read or grep, with
the original JSON kept beside each record as the source of truth.

kura builds its reads and its downloads on the engine of ytb-cli
(https://github.com/tamnd/ytb-cli), which it imports directly: the no-key
InnerTube transport, the renderer-walking parsers, the normalized
Video/Channel/Playlist/Comment types, the caption, chapter and SponsorBlock
sidecars, and above all the pure-Go native download engine (the token-free
ANDROID_VR client, the goja nsig solver, the ranged concurrent fetcher, and the
yt-dlp-compatible format selector). It adds only the archive-shaped pieces ytb-cli
never needed: a repository on disk, a media and stream localiser, and the HTML and
Markdown renderers.

